05676nam a22010575i 9780520915015DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209150157 a10.1525/97805209150152doi  a(DE-B1597)544390  a(OCoLC)1149446577  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBL64.R48bJ84 1993 E-BOOK 7aREL0170002bisacsh04a320.552201 aJuergensmeyer, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New Cold War? :bReligious Nationalism Confronts the Secular State /cMark Juergensmeyer.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Studies in Religion and Society ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface to the Paperback Edition -- tIntroduction: The Rise of Religious Nationalism -- tPart One: Religion vs. Secular Nationalism -- t1. The Loss of Faith in Secular Nationalism -- t2. Competing Ideologies of Order -- tPart Two: The Global Confrontations -- t3. Models of Religious Revolution: The Middle East -- t4. Political Targets of Religion: South Asia -- t5. Religious Ambivalence toward Socialist Nationalism: Formerly Marxist States -- tPart Three: The Problems Ahead -- t6. Why Religious Confrontations Are Violent -- t7. Democracy, Human Rights, and the Modern Religious State -- tConclusion: Can We Live with Religious Nationalism? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tList of Interviews -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWill the religious confrontations with secular authorities around the world lead to a new Cold War? Mark Juergensmeyer paints a provocative picture of the new religious revolutionaries altering the political landscape in the Middle East, South Asia, Central Asia, and Eastern Europe. Impassioned Muslim leaders in Egypt, Palestine, and Algeria, political rabbis in Israel, militant Sikhs in India, and triumphant Catholic clergy in Eastern Europe are all players in Juergensmeyer's study of the explosive growth of religious movements that decisively reject Western ideas of secular nationalism.Juergensmeyer revises our notions of religious revolutions. Instead of viewing religious nationalists as wild-eyed, anti-American fanatics, he reveals them as modern activists pursuing a legitimate form of politics. He explores the positive role religion can play in the political life of modern nations, even while acknowledging some religious nationalists' proclivity to violence and disregard of Western notions of human rights. Finally, he situates the growth of religious nationalism in the context of the political malaise of the modern West. Noting that the synthesis of traditional religion and secular nationalism yields a religious version of the modern nation-state, Juergensmeyer claims that such a political entity could conceivably embrace democratic values and human rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNationalismxReligious aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aReligion and statexHistoryy20th century. 0aRevolutionsxReligious aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aactivism.  aalgeria.  acatholicism.  acentral asia.  achristianity.  aclergy.  acomparative religion.  aeastern europe.  aegypt.  ahistory.  ahuman rights.  aindia.  aislam.  aisrael.  ajudaica.  ajudaism.  aliberal democracy.  amiddle east.  amodern west.  anational identity.  anationalism.  anonfiction.  apalestine.  apolitical philosophy.  apolitical science.  apolitics.  arabbis.  areligion.  areligious leaders.  areligious movements.  areligious nat